{
  "text": "A change in language policy is most obviously necessary for deaf babies who are now being implanted, the present group of toddlers and preschoolers, and to some extent for students in primary school. These groups form the focal point of the remainder of our discussion. Meanwhile, bilingual education, with a natural sign language as the language of instruction, still seems most preferable for many deaf students in secondary and postsecondary education, and we believe there is sufficient empirical evidence to support that view (e.g., [CITATION_1] .",
